TY  - JOUR
T1  - Intraday Volatility in International Stock Index Futures Markets: Meteor Showers or Heat Waves?
AU  - Booth, G. Geoffrey
AU  - Chowdhury, Mustafa
AU  - Martikainen, Teppo
AU  - Tse, Yiuman
Y1  - 1997/11/01
PY  - 1997
DA  - 1997/11/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.43.11.1564
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.43.11.1564
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1564
EP  - 1576
VL  - 43
IS  - 11
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - The international transmission of intraday price volatility among the United States, United Kingdom, and Japanese stock index futures markets in the period 1988?1994 is investigated in this paper. The empirical results based on extreme-value estimators and vector autoregression indicate the rapid transmission of information between markets. The volatilities of the U.S. and U.K. futures markets appear to follow a meteor shower rather than a heat wave type of process. This means that these volatilities react to shocks from other markets, i.e., they cannot be described only by their past values. However, the heat wave hypothesis is not rejected for the Japanese market, meaning that the shocks to Japanese volatility are mostly country-specific. A multivariate GARCH model supports the U.K. and Japanese but not the U.S. results.
AB  - The international transmission of intraday price volatility among the United States, United Kingdom, and Japanese stock index futures markets in the period 1988?1994 is investigated in this paper. The empirical results based on extreme-value estimators and vector autoregression indicate the rapid transmission of information between markets. The volatilities of the U.S. and U.K. futures markets appear to follow a meteor shower rather than a heat wave type of process. This means that these volatilities react to shocks from other markets, i.e., they cannot be described only by their past values. However, the heat wave hypothesis is not rejected for the Japanese market, meaning that the shocks to Japanese volatility are mostly country-specific. A multivariate GARCH model supports the U.K. and Japanese but not the U.S. results.
SN  - 0025-1909
